{% block article_content %}
  {% call heading(tag="h2") %}
    Understanding computational analysis
  {% endcall %}
  <p>
    Computational analysis includes activities such as any programmatic searching in bulk across the Find Case Law records to identify, extract or enrich contents within the records.
  </p>
  <p>This means using automated or algorithmic methods to process large numbers of judgments systematically.</p>
  {% call heading(tag="h3") %}
    Examples of computational analysis
  {% endcall %}
  <p>Computational analysis includes activities like:</p>
  {% call list(variant="bullets") %}
    {% call list_item() %}
      text mining across large numbers of judgments
    {% endcall %}
    {% call list_item() %}
      natural language processing of judgment text
    {% endcall %}
    {% call list_item() %}
      bulk extraction of data from judgments
    {% endcall %}
    {% call list_item() %}
      machine learning or AI training on judgment datasets
    {% endcall %}
    {% call list_item() %}
      statistical analysis across the full collection
    {% endcall %}
    {% call list_item() %}
      automated identification or classification of judgments
    {% endcall %}
  {% endcall %}
  {% call heading(tag="h3") %}
    What's not computational analysis
  {% endcall %}
  <p>Standard uses that don't require a licence include:</p>
  {% call list(variant="bullets") %}
    {% call list_item() %}
      reading individual judgments
    {% endcall %}
    {% call list_item() %}
      downloading judgments one at a time as you need them
    {% endcall %}
    {% call list_item() %}
      using the search function to find cases
    {% endcall %}
    {% call list_item() %}
      incorporating judgments into commercial products or services
    {% endcall %}
    {% call list_item() %}
      quoting or citing judgments in your work
    {% endcall %}
  {% endcall %}
  <p>These uses are all covered by the Open Justice Licence.</p>
  {% call heading(tag="h2") %}
    Do you need a licence?
  {% endcall %}
  <p>
    You need a licence if you want to perform any programmatic searching in bulk across Find Case Law records to identify, extract or enrich contents within the records.
  </p>
  <p>
    You don't need a licence if your use is covered by the Open Justice Licence, including commercial products that incorporate judgments.
  </p>
  {% call heading(tag="h2") %}
    No costs to apply
  {% endcall %}
  <p>There are no costs to apply for a licence to perform computational analysis.</p>
  {% call card(title="How to apply", title_tag="h2") %}
    <p>
      Visit
      {% call link(href=url("transactional-licence-form-page-3")) %}
        What you need to apply for a licence
      {%- endcall -%}
      {{ " " }}to understand the application requirements, or go straight to
      {% call link() %}
        Licence application process
      {%- endcall -%}
      {{ " " }}to learn about how applications are assessed.
    </p>
    <p>
      If you're uncertain whether your intended use counts as computational analysis, contact us at
      {% call link(href="mailto:caselawlicence@nationalarchives.gov.uk") %}
        caselawlicence@nationalarchives.gov.uk
      {%- endcall -%}
      {{ " " }}to discuss your needs.
    </p>
    <p>It's better to ask than to proceed without permission if a licence is required.</p>
  {% endcall %}
{% endblock article_content %}
